{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> ναίω</b>, <br /> poet. Verb, <i>active</i> (<i>intransitive</i>) only in <i>present</i> and <i>imperfect</i> (<i>Epic dialect</i> ναίεσκον [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 5.708), \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<i>future</i> and <i>aorist</i> in causal and <i>middle</i> and <i>passive</i> forms, see below [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 11, 111: \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__1</b></Level3> of persons, <b>dwell, abide</b>, mostly followed by a <i>preposition</i> of Place, ἐν Λῃ, etc., Il.[same place], etc.; ῥοῇς ἔπι Σαγγαρίοιο [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 16.719; ἐπ᾽ ἄκρων ὀρέων 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Tyrannus” 1105 (Lyric poetry); κατὰ πτόλιν 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 2.130; ἀν᾽ οὔρεα 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Theogonia” 130; πὰρ ποταμόν 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 2.522; ὑπὸ Πλάκῳ 6.396: with _dative_ loci, αἰθέρι ναίων 2.412, 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Opera et Dies” 18, etc.; ν. μετά τινος 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Philoctetes” 1105 (Lyric poetry): _metaphorically_, τὴν σὴν δ᾽ ὁμοῦ ναίουσαν [ὀργήν] [prev. author] “OT” 338; τὰν ἀρετὰν ναίειν ἐπὶ πέτραις 4th-5th c.BC: Simonides Lyricus 58 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: with <i>adverb</i>, [κακότης] ἐγγύθι ναίει [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Opera et Dies” 288; ἵνα αἱ Φορκίδες ναίουσι 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Prometheus Vinctus” 794 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]. b. with <i>accusative</i> loci, <b>dwell in, inhabit</b>, οἰκία, δώματα, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 20.288, 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Opera et Dies” 8, compare 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 7.5, +others\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ἅλα, πλάκας ὀρέων, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Helena” 1584, “Ba.” 719; frequently with place-names, 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 2.615, 2nd c.AD: Alexander Rhetor 22, etc.: _metaphorically_, Πειθὼ ναίει καὶ Χάρις υἱὸν Ἄγησίλα uncertain in 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “Fragmenta.” 123.10 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; of the statues of gods, πρόπυλα ναίουσιν τάδε [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Electra” 1375 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]:—<i>passive</i>, <b>to be inhabited</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “fragment” 1125 (in _aorist_ ἐνάσθη), etc.\">Refs</a>]; πολίταις [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus 16.88; ὑπ᾽ ἀνδράσι 3rd c.BC: Apollonius Rhodius Epicus 1.794. \">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> of places, <b>lie, be situated</b>, once in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus, νήσων αἳ ναίουσι πέρην ἁλός 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 2.626; ὦ κλεινὰ Σαλαμίς, σὺ μέν που ναίεις ἁλίπλακτος 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Ajax” 598 (Lyric poetry). \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> causal, in <i>Epic dialect</i> <i>aorist</i> ἔνασσα or νάσσα, <i>middle</i> ἐνασσάμην: <br /><Level3><b>__II.1</b></Level3> with <i>accusative</i> loci, <b>give</b> one <b>to dwell in</b>, καί κέ οἱ Ἄργεϊ νάσσα πόλιν I would have <b>given</b> him a town in Argos <b>for his home</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 4.174 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; <b>make habitable, build</b>, νηὸν ἔνασσαν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “hymnus ad Apollinem” 298 \">Refs</a>]; <b>settle</b>, Εὔβοιαν ἕλον καὶ ἔνασσαν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “Pae.” 5.36 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]:—in <i>middle</i>, <b>found</b>, μυρία δ᾽ ἄστη νάσσατ᾽ ἐποιχόμενος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.BC: Apollonius Rhodius Epicus 4.275:\">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>] —in <i>passive</i>, of places, like <i>active</i> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1.2 \">Refs</a>], <b>to be situated</b>, πολίων εὖ ναιομενάων [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 3.400, +others \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.2</b></Level3> with <i>accusative</i> <i>person</i>, <b>let</b> one <b>dwell, settle</b> him, ἐν Ἄργει ἔνασσεν Ἡρακλέος ἐκγόνους [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 5.71 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]:— in <i>middle</i>, νάσσατο κούρην [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.BC: Apollonius Rhodius Epicus 4.567. \">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__III</b></Level2> <i>middle</i> and <i>passive</i> in <i>active</i> sense, <i>future</i> νάσσομαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] 2.747 \">Refs</a>]: <i>Epic dialect</i> <i>aorist 1</i> νάσσατο [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Opera et Dies” 639, 3rd c.BC(?): Demosthenes Bithynus Epicus 6, 4th-3rd c.BC: Philetas 24\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; later <i>3rd.pers.</i> <i>plural</i> ναιήσαντο [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Dionysius Periegeta 349 \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]: <i>perfect</i> νένασται [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “IG” 14.1389i8 \">Refs</a>]; <i>participle</i> νενασμένος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Dionysius Periegeta 264: \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]<i>aorist</i> <i>passive</i> ἐνάσθην, πατὴρ ἐμὸς Ἄργεϊ νάσθη my father <b>settled</b> at Argos, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 14.119.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>] —More frequently in Compos. with ἀπό, κατά.","strongNumber":"G8373","accentedUnicode":"ναίω","shortDef":"to inhabit","mediumDef":"to inhabit","stepGloss":"to inhabit","stepTransliteration":"naiō","count":0,"_step_Type":"verb"}]}